name: dichloroacetaldehyde
Reason: The basic hydrocarbon chain with two carbon atoms (ethane) has a melting point of around -183°C. Functional groups will influence this base value: (1) Two chloro (Cl-) groups would tend to increase the melting point due to their higher molecular weight and polar nature, as each chloro group introduces dipole-dipole interactions making the molecules attract each other more, leading to an increased melting point compared to the base hydrocarbon. For estimating, each chloro group might contribute an increase of around +40 to +50°C. (2) The aldehyde (C=O) group typically will lower the melting point due to hindering close packing of the molecules, since the structure is less symmetrical and has a strong dipole. The decrease due to the aldehyde may be on the order of -20 to -30°C.

name: dichloroacetaldehyde
Reason: To predict the melting point of dichloroacetaldehyde (ClCH(Cl)CHO), we will consider the effects of the functional groups compared to a reference compound. Acetaldehyde (CH3CHO) has a melting point of -123°C. Dichloroacetaldehyde has two chlorine atoms which are both electron-withdrawing and significantly larger than hydrogen atoms. Chlorines will raise the melting point due to an increase in molecular weight, polarizability, and dipole moment which can lead to stronger intermolecular forces (especially Van der Waals forces and dipole-dipole interactions). Each chlorine atom can be estimated to raise the melting point by approximately 40-50°C compared to hydrogen. However, the value needs to be adjusted since there will be diminishing returns with additional substituents, the push towards a higher melting point won't be as dramatic for the second chlorine atom.
